Overview:

This directory contains code for a working 'databrowser' that can be used as a 
starting point for creating other scientific databrowsers. The goal is to 
provide code that allows for easy configuration of end-to-end functionality
for internactive data visualization using the R statistical analysis package.


================================================================================

Prerequisites:

Python         - http://python.org/

R              - http://www.r-project.org/

rpy2           - http://rpy.sourceforge.net/

Support for PDF files has additional requirements:

Ghostscript    - http://ghostscript.com

ImageMagick    - http://imagemagick.org
- OR -
GraphicsMagick - http://graphicsmagick.org


================================================================================

From client to back end the parts are as follows:

User Interface Contents (HTML)
 * index.html

User Interface Behavior (javascript)
 * ./behavior

User Interface Style (CSS)
 * ./style

CGI script (Python)
 * __Databrowser.cgi

Back end Analysis (R)
 * ./R

Debugging information generated by CGI
 * DEBUG.txt
 * TRANSCRIPT.txt

Directory for (English language) output graphics generated by CGI
 * output_en/

Automated installation (make)
 * Makefile
 * Makefile_vars_~.mk -- configurable variables


================================================================================

Initial installation procedure:

1) Edit config/Makefile_vars_YOURSERVER to point to existing directories on your server.

2) Install the code:

$ sudo make install location=YOURSERVER
$ sudo make install_cache location=YOURSERVER

3) Test whether the CGI functions from the command line:

$ /CGI_LOCATION/DATABROWSER.cgi
Content-type: application/json

{"status": "OK", "img_url": "output/55a411c2081ba0e86405cfa159989cc8283a43f843946c8e5ca8e807d2867672.png", "return_values": [1.0, 2.0, 3.0, 4.0]}

4) Test things from the web browser:

http://localhost/URL_PATH_TO_DATABROWSER/

5) Check the debug and transcript files for hints and lines of code to run in R

$ make debug location=YOURSERVER
$ make transcript location=YOURSERVER



